elements.2211.03216_d4b324125ebeaa58f4d3f87deeb66: As the demand for user privacy grows, controlled data removal (machine unlearning) is becoming an important feature of machine learning models for data-sensitive Web applications such as social networks and recommender systems
elements.2211.03216_0dc13a3aa7de12bb2799e28315856: Nevertheless, at this point it is still largely unknown how to perform efficient machine unlearning of graph neural networks (GNNs); this is especially the case when the number of training samples is small, in which case unlearning can seriously compromise the performance of the model
elements.2211.03216_90b3302ed9b5a11824e058d95b4d4: To address this issue, we initiate the study of unlearning the Graph Scattering Transform (GST), a mathematical framework that is efficient, provably stable under feature or graph topology perturbations, and offers graph classification performance comparable to that of GNNs
elements.2211.03216_e68e0e6e29078dc8767507d6108e9: Our main contribution is the first known nonlinear approximate graph unlearning method based on GSTs
elements.2211.03216_cf56d5754fe029448467deb438307: Our second contribution is a theoretical analysis of the computational complexity of the proposed unlearning mechanism, which is hard to replicate for deep neural networks
elements.2211.03216_04304b583abc09a28ad758053c69d: Our third contribution are extensive simulation results which show that, compared to complete retraining of GNNs after each removal request, the new GST-based approach offers, on average, a
elements.2211.03216_6a145847dcd5a3fe482fa2f14a01f: x speed-up and leads to a
elements.2211.03216_cd90de9ae69ca350240b545e66804: increase in test accuracy during unlearning of
elements.2211.03216_1e47c4d6cafa22c9d41017ab5b6a4: training graphs from the IMDB dataset (
elements.2211.03216_f4816489b9e69c84b10d104c5e457: Graph classification is a learning task that frequently arises in real-world Web applications related to social network analysis
elements.2211.03216_e5310a948cc90bd38e13bf79b360b: While the availability of large sets of user training data has contributed to the deployment of modern deep learning models
elements.2211.03216_d1d51a525961c35dd45d81a655941: for solving graph classification problems, deep learners mostly fail to comply with new data privacy regulations
elements.2211.03216_e3d175981fbbb9fb1253a8a7bfe1f: Among them is the right of users to remove their data from the dataset and eliminate their contribution to all models trained on it
elements.2211.03216_b40d8f134227e5af7ab4bed3b529a: and have to be taken into consideration during the model training process
elements.2211.03216_f463da8743f72a94989ca50460943: We consider for the first time the problem of removing nodes from possibly different training graphs used in graph classification models
elements.2211.03216_99e37f4883ba4a76e9716a12cb099: Examples where such requests arise include users (nodes) withdrawing from some interest groups (subgraphs) in social networks, and users deleting their browsing histories for online shopping, which corresponds to the removal of an entire graph from the training set
elements.2211.03216_80cc93d091b2182846d7c1121479d: Note that only removing user data from a dataset is insufficient to guarantee the desired level of privacy, since the training data can be potentially reconstructed from the trained models
elements.2211.03216_646a86cbdbd4a0b92390bbff80fd6: Naively, one can always retrain the model from scratch with the remaining dataset to ensure complete privacy; however, this is either computationally expensive or infeasible due to the high frequency of data removal requests
elements.2211.03216_f2e515493ffe5910517664dcdd4de: Another possible approach is to use differential privacy based methods to accommodate data removal during training
elements.2211.03216_cdb453c2f19e767be3dfc354229b2: However, most state-of-the-art DP-GNNs focus on node classification instead of graph classification tasks, and it remains an open problem to design efficient GNNs for graph classification problem while preserving node-level privacy
elements.2211.03216_6d59174e8e2415ff30a77ecd63056: Recently, the data removal problem has also motivated a new line of research on
elements.2211.03216_364da4fc55cce8dc536c75a9c223b: , which aims to efficiently eliminate the influence of certain data points on a model
elements.2211.03216_1d4d241ae57205114453073aca23f: While various kinds of unlearning algorithms exist, most of the existing literature, especially that pertaining to deep neural networks, does not discuss model training and unlearning in the limited training data regime, which is often the case in practice
elements.2211.03216_7939661323323f8b3ae74a5ee82f0: Unlearning in this case may degrade the model performance drastically, and as a result, efficient and accurate graph classification and unlearning with limited training data is still an open problem
elements.2211.03216_656d998ea572c42f3f61bc560d549: Concurrently, a mathematical approach known as the Graph Scattering Transform (GST) has been used as a nontrainable counterpart of GNNs that can be applied to any type of trainable classification
elements.2211.03216_387ac622f41525bb1f1be81338845: GST iteratively applies graph wavelets and nonlinear activations on the input graph signals which may be viewed as forward passes of GNNs without trainable parameters
elements.2211.03216_715f1671f316bc0603d15bc30e913: It has been shown that GSTs can not only remain stable under small perturbations of graph features and topologies
elements.2211.03216_e4b5796e9589ba6f78c3bc4f7be49: , but also compete with many types of GNNs on solving different graph classification problems
elements.2211.03216_45496d4a5adf6bde6f4ed6b313c36: Furthermore, since all wavelet coefficients in GSTs are constructed analytically, GST is computationally more efficient and requires less training data compared to GNNs when combined with the same trainable classifiers
elements.2211.03216_ecc3cf578fae3dc319bb22dd994f1: As a result, GSTs are frequently used in practice
elements.2211.03216_3a3f31359c50cc220491c773f128a: , especially in the limited training data regime
elements.2211.03216_07d99bab4656e6dbce34c02c78bd1: Furthermore, it also allows for deriving theoretical analysis on nonlinear models for graph embedding, and the related conclusions could potentially shed some light on the design of GNNs that are more suitable for data removals.
